{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe compact/delete/init contended-lock tests plant a lock then start a\n`threading.Timer(0.4, unlink)` and assert only `rc == 0` plus snapshot/tombstone presence\n(`tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_compact_index_lock.py:71-85`,\n`tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_delete_init_index_lock.py:83-119`). On a slow runner the\n0.4s timer removes the lock before git's first attempt, so the test passes through the\nordinary success path without ever exercising `_with_index_lock_retry`\n(`gitutil.py:110-129`). VALIDATED.\n\n## What\n1. Add an instrumented test seam to `_with_index_lock_retry` in `src/rebar/_store/gitutil.py`,\n   following the EXACT precedent of the `_reclaim_probe` seam already added to this same module\n   for story sundried-bonny-sloth (df83): a module-level `_retry_probe: Callable[[int,\n   subprocess.CompletedProcess], None] | None = None`.\n   - **Type of `result`:** the `subprocess.CompletedProcess` returned by `run_once()` — the\n     SAME type `run_once` already returns (`Callable[[], subprocess.CompletedProcess]`). Tests\n     inspect `result.returncode` and reuse the module's own `_is_index_lock_error(result.stderr\n     or result.stdout or \"\")` to assert the first attempt was a genuine index.lock error.\n   - **Where it fires (every attempt, incl. the pre-loop call):** invoked once immediately\n     after the INITIAL `run_once()` at `gitutil.py:120` (as `attempt_number=1`), and again\n     immediately after each in-loop `run_once()` at `gitutil.py:128`. `attempt_number` for the\n     in-loop calls is `attempt + 1` where the loop variable `attempt` runs `1..\n     _INDEX_LOCK_ATTEMPTS-1` — so the sequence observed is 1, 2, 3, … matching real attempts.\n   - **Production is unaffected:** the default is `None`, so the invocation is guarded\n     (`if _retry_probe is not None: _retry_probe(...)`) and skipped in production. Callers that\n     import `_with_index_lock_retry` by name (e.g. `event_append.py:45,211,219`) see no behavior\n     change because the seam stays `None` outside tests. The probe is invoked directly (not\n     wrapped in try/except): in production it is never set, and a test owns its own probe's\n     behavior, so a probe raising surfaces as that test's own failure — the desired contract.\n   - **No teardown footgun:** tests set the seam via pytest `monkeypatch.setattr(gitutil,\n     \"_retry_probe\", …)`, which auto-restores it to `None` at test teardown (no manual reset,\n     no cross-test leakage) — identical to how the df83 `_reclaim_probe` seam is used.\n2. Rewrite the three contended-lock tests to use the seam instead of `threading.Timer`: plant a\n   fresh (young, not reclaimable-as-stale) lock; the probe, on observing the first attempt fail\n   with an index.lock error, unlinks the planted lock so the NEXT attempt succeeds (deterministic\n   synchronization — the lock is released strictly after the confirmed first failure, never\n   before). Assert at least two attempts occurred and that attempt 1's result was a genuine\n   index.lock error. The now-unused `threading.Timer`-based `_plant_fresh_lock` timer branch is\n   removed/updated so no test still relies on timing.\n3. Add a dedicated non-lock-failure test in each of the two files: using the same seam to count\n   attempts, drive a NON-index.lock git failure (e.g. a commit that fails for an unrelated\n   reason) and assert the probe saw exactly ONE attempt (the non-lock failure returns\n   immediately, never retried).\n\n## Scope\n- `src/rebar/_store/gitutil.py` — add the `_retry_probe` seam to `_with_index_lock_retry`\n  (guarded, default None; fires on the pre-loop attempt and every in-loop attempt).\n- `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_compact_index_lock.py` — deterministic ride-out test +\n  a non-lock-not-retried test; drop the `threading.Timer` reliance.\n- `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_delete_init_index_lock.py` — deterministic ride-out tests\n  (delete + init) + a non-lock-not-retried test; update/remove the timer-based\n  `_plant_fresh_lock` branch.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] First attempt deterministically returns the real `index.lock` error before the lock is\n      released (synchronized via the `_retry_probe` seam, not a timer).\n- [ ] Each rewritten contended-lock test asserts at least two attempts occurred (retry path\n      exercised) and that the first attempt was a genuine index.lock error.\n- [ ] A dedicated test in each file asserts a non-lock git failure returns on the FIRST\n      attempt and is never retried (probe observed exactly one attempt).\n- [ ] The final event/commit (snapshot/tombstone) exists; `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783792832350322001,"uuid":"2a609575-4318-417d-9224-6e68df587e7c"}